	<main>
		<img width="2500" height="1201" src="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-doggerland.jpg" class="singlepostthumb wp-post-image" alt="illustration of mesolithic settlement" decoding="async" fetchpriority="high" srcset="https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-doggerland.jpg 2500w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-doggerland-520x250.jpg 520w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-doggerland-1200x576.jpg 1200w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-doggerland-768x369.jpg 768w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-doggerland-1536x738.jpg 1536w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-doggerland-2048x984.jpg 2048w, https://hakaimagazine.com/wp-content/uploads/header-doggerland-900x432.jpg 900w" sizes="(max-width: 2500px) 100vw, 2500px" /><div class="post-thumbnail-caption">Where and how did the people of the submerged territory of Doggerland live before rising seas pushed them away thousands of years ago? An archaeologist and his colleagues are getting closer to finding out with the help of technology. Illustration by Christian Jegou/Science Photo Library</div>
			<article class="main container col4">
								<header class="maincol">
										<h1 class="pagetitle">Conjuring the Lost Land Beneath the North Sea</h1>
										<h2 class="dek singlepagecontainer">New research reveals that Doggerland—a sunken swath of Europe connecting Britain to the mainland—was more than a simple thoroughfare. It was home.</h2>
										<section class="singlebyline singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Authored by</h3>
						by  
										<a href="https://hakaimagazine.com/profiles/tristan-mcconnell/" class="tagmanager" id="author_link_top" >Tristan McConnell</a>								<br/>
												</section>
					 
					<aside class="singlebydatewords singlepagecontainer">
						<h3 class="invis">Wordcount</h3>
						December 5, 2024 | 4,400 words, about 22 minutes
					</aside>

					
				</header>

				
